@ole555 I don't necessarily disagree with a lot of what you're saying. Every social problem in the west today can be narrowed down to the capitalist-consumerist economic model. But I don't see that as having much to do with technological innovation in and of itself. Just as building tools to hunt was innovation in the stone age, so too is AI today - and it is a natural evolution of "machines that can produce all of the basic material requisites for human thriving with very little human labour". We'd be much better at meeting everyone's needs if machines managed everything, in theory, I don't believe that to be true.Â 

Sure the structures upon which it is built, the infrastructure it relies upon such as the internet, and the organisations that ultimately control them are problematic, given that their ultimate goal is to grow indefinitely - which we know by now is detrimental to human society. That is a undeniably a problem. But my optimism also comes from where I am situated. I research trust in AI, in Sweden, and work closely with other researchers that have been instrumental in AI governance mechanisms in the EU, which in many ways is leading the world. Based on the existing laws the EU has already sanctioned giants like Google, and got Apple to make fundamental changes in their operations. And the upcoming legal framework is going to be instrumental in reigning in the power some of these large corporations wield. It also leads the world in climate change initiatives and the like, albeit within the framework of a broken system. But I believe in incremental change rather than a revolution, those things are proven to be bad for everyone.Â 

Within this context, I have every reason to be (cautiously) optimistic, while acknowledging the larger systemic problems. I can't, however, outright reject the system, I can only challenge it with the hope to move the needle a little. There's a difference between what you know and what you can do with that knowledge. I am a not a techno-solutionist, but I genuinely believe that AI does have the potential to be a great equaliser, and I don't disagree that it also has the potential to be the greatest oppressor. Ultimately it is just a tool (for the most part). And you're right to be worried about who controls it and what their motives are. I just so happen to be in a part of the world where I have some faith in the system.

