@Jimbo MacGee to be fair, especially in data science and AI, if anyone says "fair/equal", they're stupid or lying. We've been trying to describe these terms for hundreds or thousands of years without success. The majority of modern AI development is about developing ways around bias in data. 
There is also an opposing approach, which basically boils down to that you're asking an AI information assistant this: "what [on the internet] do people think about [the validity of] QAnon". Because the context is inferred, the stark reality is, you'll probably get biased answers even from millions of parameters and billions of training inputs. Why? Because the context is biased.
So do we stay truth to an ideal of whatever 'fair' should mean, do we represent reality, which is that our context is flawed and biased, or do we state facts, and facts only, where it is us, who select what constitue fact, and what's fiction? There is no right answer, and this fact, unless an AI winter looms in on us, will quickly change alot of things.

